            <lb/>
Geology Lecture<lb/>
1811<lb/>
- So different are the exertions<lb/>
of the faculties of the mind, &amp; so<lb/>
infinitely various the combinations of our<lb/>
ideas;  <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">that the same objects</hi> may be<lb/>
examined with the most opposite<lb/>
views, &amp; considered under many<lb/>
diversified and beautiful relations. -<lb/>
- - It is on this fact of our nature<lb/>
so familiar to every understanding, that<lb/>
the great extent and progression of Science<lb/>
&amp; Philosophy depend. - -<lb/>
- Hence their division into various branches<lb/>
&amp; hence the distinctness &amp; accuracy of the<lb/>
different species of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Knowledge</hi>
            <lb/>
- - The Planet that we inhabit may be<lb/>
considered in its connection with the general<lb/>
System of the Universe, as acted upon by<lb/>
gravitation, , &amp; revolving around the Sun. - -<lb/>
It may be examined as the abode of<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="2"
                xml:id="pb-2"
                facs="#i2"/>
            <lb/>
organization &amp; life, covered with vegetables<lb/>
&amp; peopled with animals; or it maybe<lb/>
studied as composed of different inorganic<lb/>
parts variously managed, &amp; subservient<lb/>
to different uses. - -<lb/>
- - It is under this last point of view<lb/>
that it is the subject of Geology. - The<lb/>
word is derived from the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Greek language</hi>
            <lb/>
it signifies the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Science of the Earth</hi>;<lb/>
but its acceptation is limited, &amp; it is only<lb/>
applied to the branch of knowledge<lb/>
relating to the nature, position, &amp;<lb/>
changes of the bodies that compose<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">known</hi> parts of the surface<lb/>
of the Globe. - -<lb/>
- |_ The outlines of the Science<lb/>
are plain &amp; obvious &amp; they may<lb/>
be <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">made evident</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">illustrated</add> even <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">from</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">by</add> common<lb/>
observation, from a superficial view<lb/>
of Nature; - - I shall attempt<lb/>
a delineation of them which <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">perhaps</del> I hope will<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="3"
                xml:id="pb-3"
                facs="#i3"/>
            <lb/>
be found an appropriate introduction to the<lb/>
study of the science &amp; I shall point out the order<lb/>
in which they will be considered in these lectures. -<lb/>
The first impressions received from<lb/>
the exterior of the Globe are those of<lb/>
diversity, variety &amp; beauty. - -<lb/>
Hills, Valiles &amp; Plains appear covered<lb/>
with different soils &amp; affording<lb/>
different vegetables. Mountain<lb/>
chains are seen presenting irregular<lb/>
summits, bare or capped with<lb/>
snow, or emitting volcanic fires,<lb/>
&amp; their foundations form, the beds<lb/>
of rivers, or the shores of Lakes,<lb/>
Seas &amp; the Ocean. - -<lb/>
- - In different Mountains &amp;<lb/>
Rocks there are two remarkable<lb/>
distinctions of arrangement. -<lb/>
|_ - Some are irregularly heaped together<lb/>
in large masses, or layers which are<lb/>
divided almost perpendicularly to the<lb/>
surface . -<lb/>
Others are arranged in bands or<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="4"
                xml:id="pb-4"
                facs="#i4"/>
            <lb/>
Strata, parallel or very slightly<lb/>
inclined to the horizon. - -<lb/>
The first consist for the most part<lb/>
of Chrystalline stony matter, they<lb/>
contain few fragments; and exhibit<lb/>
few vestiges of a former order of things. -<lb/>
These are called Primary Rocks. -<lb/>
- - The second order usually contains<lb/>
abundance of Mechanical deposited,<lb/>
water worn stones, sand, &amp; even clay<lb/>
&amp; they often abound in vegetable<lb/>
remains, &amp; the exuviae of marine<lb/>
animals, These are called<lb/>
the secondary Rocks. - - -<lb/>
sketches<lb/>
- Both these great Orders of Rocks<lb/>
contain <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">Rocks</del> Dykes or veins which<lb/>
are more or less perpendicular &amp;<lb/>
which have been fissures or chasms<lb/>
filled with different substances<lb/>
embracing a variety of metallic ores<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="5"
                xml:id="pb-5"
                facs="#i5"/>
            <lb/>
2<lb/>
- The Primary &amp; Secondary Rocks,<lb/>
their transitions into, or relations to, each<lb/>
other, &amp; the different substances they<lb/>
contain, are the first &amp; most important<lb/>
objects of study in Geological Science,<lb/>
&amp; they will be the first to occupy<lb/>
our attention in this Couse of Lectures. -<lb/>
- The variety, the shades of<lb/>
difference seem almost infinite, yet<lb/>
their relations are capable of becoming<lb/>
the objects of distinct study. |_ The<lb/>
Rocks of different districts where there<lb/>
is a considerable extent of surface,<lb/>
are generally found of the same species.<lb/>
Similar varieties have similar assocations<lb/>
in Climates the most distant, &amp; the<lb/>
chasms or veins they infold<lb/>
usually contain the same metals, &amp; the<lb/>
same crystallized bodies. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="6"
                xml:id="pb-6"
                facs="#i6"/>
            <lb/>
- . |_ The Arrangements of Rocks<lb/>
&amp; Mountains in Nature <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>xxxxxxxx</unclear>
            </del> &amp;<lb/>
of the minerals they contain<lb/>
are admirably adapted to<lb/>
the occurring of things, &amp; these<lb/>
arrangements will be pointed<lb/>
out and discussed. - |_ The<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">irregularity of the surface</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">s</del> Metallic ores so useful<lb/>
in the Arts of life, which<lb/>
would be noxious if distributed<lb/>
over the surface of the Globe<lb/>
are concealed within its bosom<lb/>
where they revive to awaken &amp; employ<lb/>
Men in industry &amp; ingenuity.<lb/>
|_The <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">irregularities</hi> of the surface<lb/>
so <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">calculated to delight</hi>
            <lb/>
the eye, by their sublimity <lb/>
or their beauty, are absolutely<lb/>
essential to the order of the<lb/>
system. They diversify &amp; equalize<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="7"
                xml:id="pb-7"
                facs="#i7"/>
            <lb/>
The temperature of the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">surface</del> earth<lb/>
- The cooling agency of the highlands<lb/>
is a cause of rain &amp; vivifying<lb/>
dews - <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">They modify the course</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of the winds</del> the water raised in vapour<lb/>
from the ocean, is condensed<lb/>
on their summits, and flows in<lb/>
springs &amp; streams &amp; rivers, to<lb/>
produce vegetation &amp; multiply<lb/>
life, in y<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">e</hi> Vallies &amp; plains.<lb/>
After considering <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">in the first</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">place</del>, the existing order of<lb/>
things <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">the facts which</del> in the forms which<lb/>
at the moment appear permanent<lb/>
the next step in the enquiry<lb/>
will be the laws of their<lb/>
alterations. -<lb/>
|_ On this subject the human<lb/>
powers are necessarily limited<lb/>
We have as yet penetrated<lb/>
to a small depth only below<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="8"
                xml:id="pb-8"
                facs="#i8"/>
            <lb/>
the surface; &amp; there may be<lb/>
an interior mechanism in<lb/>
the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <unclear>xxxx</unclear>
            </del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">centre</add> of which we have<lb/>
no knowledge - The effects<lb/>
of Heat, light, air &amp;<lb/>
water upon the surface<lb/>
are almost the only circumstances<lb/>
which we are capable of accurately<lb/>
studying, &amp; even with respect<lb/>
to these our sphere of observation<lb/>
is very small, |_ the works<lb/>
of Ages cannot be judged<lb/>
of except very imperfectly<lb/>
by their effects in hours or<lb/>
days, the laws of infinite<lb/>
wisdom cannot be fully<lb/>
estimated by finite intelligence<lb/>
yet there is a glory in<lb/>
the effort &amp; delight &amp;<lb/>
instruction in the result.<lb/>
            <milestone xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                       unit="section"
                       rend="line"/>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="9"
                xml:id="pb-9"
                facs="#i9"/>
            <lb/>
3<lb/>
- The Primary &amp; Secondary Rocks<lb/>
which form the known solid parts of our<lb/>
Globe, undergo at their surfaces, a<lb/>
continued series of changes. And<lb/>
the causes of their decomposition are the<lb/>
alterations of temperature to which<lb/>
they are exposed, assisted by the<lb/>
Chemical and mechanical agency of water,<lb/>
&amp; the attraction of their constituent parts<lb/>
for principles contained in the atmosphere.<lb/>
- Firm &amp; immutable at their bases<lb/>
In <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">in</add> consequence <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of Gravitation, Chemical</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">of Chemical &amp; electrical agencies</add>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">
               <add>agencies</add> attraction &amp; the attraction of cohesion</del>
            <lb/>
the parts of our Mountains wherever<lb/>
they are exposed to air &amp; moisture,<lb/>
lose their durability &amp; their stony<lb/>
texture &amp; become subservient to<lb/>
to the production &amp; the renovation of<lb/>
Soils. --<lb/>
- - From the decomposition of a<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="10"
                xml:id="pb-10"
                facs="#i10"/>
            <lb/>
variety of Rocks, &amp; from the mixture<lb/>
of their elements by the agency of water<lb/>
of streams &amp; rivers - varieties of Earth,<lb/>
result; fitted for all the different<lb/>
modifications of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">vegetable Life. -</hi>
            <lb/>
In Plains - in vallies &amp; on the low<lb/>
hills of mountains, they support plenty<lb/>
&amp; trees subservient to the nourishment<lb/>
&amp; shelter of the superior animals,<lb/>
&amp; to the uses of Man. - On heights<lb/>
where the larger plants are capable<lb/>
of growing in consequence of the<lb/>
intensity of the cold, or the force<lb/>
of the blast, grasses are still<lb/>
found, &amp; vegetable life extends<lb/>
its empire by means of mosses<lb/>
&amp; lichens, to the limits of perpetual<lb/>
snow. -<lb/>
-- When the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">effects</hi> for which<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="11"
                xml:id="pb-11"
                facs="#i11"/>
            <lb/>
decomposition seems principally to operate<lb/>
have been attained; The caused lose<lb/>
their energy; &amp; the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">surface</hi> is in a<lb/>
great measure defended by vegetation,<lb/>
&amp; by the vegetable earth, from any<lb/>
new action of the elements, &amp; novel<lb/>
matter even is accumulated upon it<lb/>
from <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">water &amp; air</hi>; which at first,<lb/>
were the principles of its decay. -<lb/>
-- By the degradation of y<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">e</hi> surfaces of<lb/>
Rocks fertile slopes are formed<lb/>
where, before there were only barren<lb/>
precipices. Lakes are filled up<lb/>
the lower parts of the beds of rivers<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">&amp; a finely</del> are diminished, &amp; a finely<lb/>
divided Earth is transported by the<lb/>
mechanical agency of water, from bleak<lb/>
or inaccessible mountains to supply<lb/>
the waste of soil in cultivated vallies<lb/>
&amp; plains. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="12"
                xml:id="pb-12"
                facs="#i12"/>
            <lb/>
- |_ Amidst the changes, &amp; circulation<lb/>
of Matter, a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">certain quantity</hi> of the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
