occupies the first place in<lb/>
systematic works. -- I shall<lb/>
treat of it in the last place<lb/>
in these lectures; - because it<lb/>
will always be a hypothetical<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">subject</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">investigation</add>. It cannot be<lb/>
in any way made a series<lb/>
of facts; Its foundations must<lb/>
be probable analogies. -<lb/>
- The most striking &amp; brilliant<lb/>
view of the subject is that<lb/>
which was developed in its<lb/>
first form by the genius of<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
