pure light. - - -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="26"
                xml:id="pb-26"
                facs="#i26"/>
            <lb/>
- The numerous gravitating agencies<lb/>
of the planets &amp; their satellites upon<lb/>
each other, &amp; upon the Sun, produce<lb/>
the simple effect of regular, harmonious,<lb/>
&amp; invariable revolutions. - <lb/>
- The functions of animal bodies<lb/>
are supported by various nourishment,<lb/>
&amp; by various Setts of organs; And<lb/>
almost all the principles of Matter<lb/>
in their various combinations are<lb/>
made essential to the existence<lb/>
&amp; the pleasures of one being. -<lb/>
In these things there is the nicest<lb/>
adaptation. -  An Order calculated<lb/>
to awaken the strongest admiration. -<lb/>
|_ We ought never to judge of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Nature</hi>
            <lb/>
by the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Generalizations</hi> which arise<lb/>
in our <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">own fancy</hi>. - We are<lb/>
compelled to seek for <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">simplicity</hi>
            <lb/>
on account of the weakness of our<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="27"
                xml:id="pb-27"
                facs="#i27"/>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">own powers</hi>. - We are incapable<lb/>
of giving perfection &amp; utility to complicated<lb/>
Machines, &amp; we are generally most<lb/>
impressed by that which approaches<lb/>
nearest to, - which most resembles<lb/>
the best of our own productions. -<lb/>
- But Man is <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">but</del> merely the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">imitator</hi>,<lb/>
the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Servant</hi> &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">interpreter</hi> of Nature -<lb/>
He <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">labours</hi> in vain when he attempts<lb/>
to reason concerning the ultimate<lb/>
tendency of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Her</hi> works, from that<lb/>
of his own. - He is the Slave<lb/>
of time; Her operations are in<lb/>
Eternity. - &amp; <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">the most sublime</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">high</add>
            <lb/>
faculties are required to catch even<lb/>
a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">glimpse</hi> of the wise &amp; wonderful<lb/>
laws, by which they are <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">governed</hi>.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="28"
                xml:id="pb-28"
                facs="#i28"/>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="29"
                xml:id="pb-29"
                facs="#i29"/>
            <lb/>
8<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Now</hi>
            <lb/>
With y<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="superscript">e</hi> critical  examination<lb/>
of the speculations &amp; hypotheses on<lb/>
Geology I shall conclude the<lb/>
Cours . - I shall spare<lb/>
no labour I shall employ<lb/>
all my <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">little</del> feeble powers to<lb/>
make the subject of it<lb/>
intelligible &amp; useful, but <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">lectures</hi>
            <lb/>
even in their best &amp; most popular form<lb/>
even when they most awaken interest,<lb/>
&amp; arrest the attention, are wholly<lb/>
inadequate to fix in the Mind, the<lb/>
principles &amp; basis of Science. -<lb/>
They may sometimes indeed in this<lb/>
case, excite the uninformed <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">mind</del> to<lb/>
Enquiry, &amp; communicate general views,<lb/>
but they can be subservient to useful &amp;<lb/>
extensive knowledge only, when <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">assisted</add> by <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">a</del>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="30"
                xml:id="pb-30"
                facs="#i30"/>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">previous, or collateral</hi> Study<lb/>
of the Subject to which they<lb/>
relate. - - -<lb/>
- - It is for this reason, that I<lb/>
I take the liberty of urging to<lb/>
those of my audience to whom<lb/>
the Science of Geology is as yet<lb/>
new, &amp; who may really wish to<lb/>
become acquainted with it as<lb/>
Students, the necessity of<lb/>
acquiring particular information<lb/>
by the examination of specimens<lb/>
&amp; by a course of reading. -<lb/>
- It is not necessary in the<lb/>
Study of mineral bodies in a<lb/>
Geological point of view, to enter<lb/>
at once upon the consideration<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="31"
                xml:id="pb-31"
                facs="#i31"/>
            <lb/>
of the whole extent of the fossile<lb/>
productions of the Earth. - -<lb/>
- The principal Rocks which form<lb/>
the great foundations of the Surface<lb/>
are comparatively few in number,<lb/>
&amp; may be very easily procured,<lb/>
&amp; at an inconsiderable expence. -<lb/>
The large sums of Money which are <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">often</add> laid<lb/>
out in Cabinets, are usually devoted<lb/>
to the collection of rare &amp; uncommon<lb/>
Minerals. - but these substances,<lb/>
though greatly interesting to the<lb/>
Mineralogist &amp; Chemist, are<lb/>
comparatively of little importance<lb/>
to the Geologist, whose object<lb/>
is to study the usual productions,<lb/>
            <lb/>
