14<lb/>
From what has been said of the<lb/>
nature &amp; methods of the Study <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">of Geology</add> It is<lb/>
evident that the accurate pursuit of it<lb/>
must occupy a <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">considerable</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">certain</add> portion of time<lb/>
&amp; demand some labour &amp; attention. -<lb/>
And a fair question may be asked,<lb/>
What are its practical uses? What<lb/>
advantages are likely to arise from it?<lb/>
What interests will it promote?<lb/>
- On this point, I might undoubtedly<lb/>
shelter myself under the general<lb/>
proposition, "that all knowledge is<lb/>
highly beneficial" - That whatever<lb/>
can awaken intellectual pleasure,<lb/>
or convey more exalted views of<lb/>
Nature, or of the human talents,<lb/>
is truly worthy of our cultivation, &amp;<lb/>
fitted for our faculties. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="52"
                xml:id="pb-52"
                facs="#i52"/>
            <lb/>
(blank page)<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="53"
                xml:id="pb-53"
                facs="#i53"/>
            <lb/>
But independent of such considerations<lb/>
must occupy a <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">considerable</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">certain</add> portion of time<lb/>
an useful Science, I may fairly say<lb/>
that <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Geology</hi> is exceedingly worthy of<lb/>
being cultivated. - And a few<lb/>
details will be sufficient to prove,<lb/>
that the information to be derived from<lb/>
it, is often applicable to important<lb/>
purposes, &amp; may in a number of<lb/>
instances be made subservient to the<lb/>
wants of Life. -<lb/>
- Fixed <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">up</del>on the Earth &amp; dependent<lb/>
for our support &amp; existence upon the<lb/>
various objects surrounding us, many<lb/>
of our necessities are supplied &amp;<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="54"
                xml:id="pb-54"
                facs="#i54"/>
            <lb/>
some of our highest comforts produced<lb/>
by the application of substances<lb/>
found in the Mineral Kingdom. -<lb/>
- The <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Soils</hi> from which our<lb/>
vegetable nourishment is raised;<lb/>
The Stones of which our habitations<lb/>
are formed, the fuel we employ<lb/>
for so many purposes, &amp; the metals<lb/>
so absolutely essential to civilized<lb/>
Man - <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">it is evident</del> are all<lb/>
objects of Geology - And as this<lb/>
Science treats of their nature,<lb/>
arrangement &amp; association, it is<lb/>
evidently the most capable of<lb/>
affording useful discoveries, with<lb/>
regard to their localities, occurrence<lb/>
&amp; <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">most useful</del>
            <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">readiest</add> application. -<lb/>
- - I have already mentioned that<lb/>
there is an order in the position<lb/>
of Rocks, by which certain species<lb/>
are almost always found, accompanying<lb/>
each other, &amp; occupying the same district. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="55"
                xml:id="pb-55"
                facs="#i55"/>
            <lb/>
15<lb/>
X<lb/>
- In a Mountainous country (for<lb/>
instance) if a rock of this nature<lb/>
occurred, which is <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">serpentine</hi>, we might<lb/>
be almost certain that this substance,<lb/>
which is <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">soap rock</hi> would be<lb/>
somewhere found in it, &amp; that<lb/>
this fossil which is <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag76"
                ref="#chemical_095"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag76">
          micaceous shist
          
        </term>
            </rs>,<lb/>
would not be far distant. - But<lb/>
in such a position it would be<lb/>
in vain to search for <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag77"
                ref="#chemical_184"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag77">
          Shell Limestone
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
or Coal. -<lb/>
- Again, where soft <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag78"
                ref="#chemical_184"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag78">
          Shell Limestone
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
occurs, there is a strong presumption,<lb/>
that soft black <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag79"
                ref="#chemical_397"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag79">
          shale
          
        </term>
            </rs> or loose <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag80"
                ref="#chemical_088"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag80">
          Sandstone
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
will be found in some contiguous<lb/>
spot, &amp; in such a Country there<lb/>
is little doubt, that at some depth<lb/>
or in some direction fossile coal<lb/>
would be discovered. -<lb/>
- - These circumstances are fundamental<lb/>
facts of the Science - &amp; the ready<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="56"
                xml:id="pb-56"
                facs="#i56"/>
            <lb/>
application of them must be immediately<lb/>
evident. - - -<lb/>
- - The person who is digging for pit<lb/>
Coal, if he meets beneath the soil,<lb/>
Serpentine or <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag81"
                ref="#chemical_095"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag81">
          micaceous
          
        </term>
            </rs> or granitic<lb/>
rock, if acquainted with the arrangement<lb/>
&amp; nature of strata, will be immediately<lb/>
instructed to give over his labour<lb/>
&amp; spare useless expence. - -<lb/>
But should he find a <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag82"
                ref="#chemical_088"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag82">
          Sandstone
          
        </term>
            </rs>,<lb/>
a substance which to an uninstructed<lb/>
eye, appears of much the same<lb/>
nature as <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag83"
                ref="#chemical_092"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag83">
          Granite
          
        </term>
            </rs>, it affords him<lb/>
some encouragement to proceed in<lb/>
his researches; &amp; a yellow or<lb/>
red ferruginous <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag84"
                ref="#chemical_088"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag84">
          Sandstone
          
        </term>
            </rs>, or a fine<lb/>
grained white <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag85"
                ref="#chemical_088"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag85">
          Sandstone
          
        </term>
            </rs>, or soft<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag86"
                ref="#chemical_398"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag86">
          slate
          
        </term>
            </rs> bearing impressions of vegetable<lb/>
leaves, would offer very strong<lb/>
indications of the substances sought for.<lb/>
For these strata are generally<lb/>
immediately incumbent on Coal. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="57"
                xml:id="pb-57"
                facs="#i57"/>
            <lb/>
- Similar reasonings may be applied<lb/>
to Metallic Veins. ---<lb/>
- - The Metal seldom or never occurs<lb/>
in Rocks of Serpentine, of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag87"
                ref="#chemical_097"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag87">
          Sienite
          
        </term>
            </rs>, or soft<lb/>
coaly <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
