                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag90">
          Basalts
          
        </term>
            </rs>. . - But they may be <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">looked</hi>
            <lb/>
for, in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">soft <rs xml:id="ttag91" ref="#chemical_092" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag91">
          Granite
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi>, in <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">hard <rs xml:id="ttag92" ref="#chemical_120" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag92">
          Shist
          
        </term>
               </rs>,</hi>
            <lb/>
&amp; in hard <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">
               <rs xml:id="ttag93" ref="#chemical_184" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag93">
          Shell Limestone
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </hi>. - And if<lb/>
in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag94"
                ref="#chemical_092"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag94">
          Granite
          
        </term>
            </rs> or <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag95"
                ref="#chemical_120"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag95">
          Shist
          
        </term>
            </rs>, a vein of white<lb/>
stone is found, running in a direction<lb/>
from East to West, there is much<lb/>
probability, that in some part of its<lb/>
depth, it may afford useful metal. -<lb/>
And if Veins of Spar occur in rocks,<lb/>
partly hollow &amp; partly filled with a<lb/>
yellow substance of this kind, which<lb/>
in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag96"
                ref="#place_021"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag96" type="place">
          Cornwall
        </name>
            </rs> is called <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag97"
                ref="#chemical_399"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag97">
          Gossan
          
        </term>
            </rs>, - It<lb/>
may be almost always concluded,<lb/>
that such veins will be productive,<lb/>
&amp; the larger quantity of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag98"
                ref="#chemical_399"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag98">
          Gossan
          
        </term>
            </rs>, the<lb/>
better the indication. - -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="58"
                xml:id="pb-58"
                facs="#i58"/>
            <lb/>
- Some very great losses &amp; failures<lb/>
have often taken place in Mining,<lb/>
from an ignorance of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">directors</hi>
            <lb/>
in the common facts of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Geology</hi>. -<lb/>
- I shall mention a remarkable instance<lb/>
that took place in <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag99"
                ref="#place_160"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag99" type="place">
          Somersetshire
        </name>
            </rs>. ---<lb/>
Some Miners from <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag100"
                ref="#place_021"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag100" type="place">
          Cornwall
        </name>
            </rs> were<lb/>
employed in working a rich <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag101"
                ref="#chemical_070"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag101">
          copper
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
vein, near <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag102"
                ref="#place_302"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag102" type="place">
          Nether Stowey
        </name>
            </rs>. - At<lb/>
a certain depth, the vein was<lb/>
crossed by a dike of stone - The<lb/>
Miners cut in their accustomed<lb/>
direction, expecting immediately<lb/>
to reach the vein, but their<lb/>
efforts were wholly unsuccessful,<lb/>
&amp; it was not till after some<lb/>
weeks &amp; much expenditure of<lb/>
Money &amp; Labour, that the object<lb/>
was attained. -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="59"
                xml:id="pb-59"
                facs="#i59"/>
            <lb/>
16<lb/>
- The reason of their failure was<lb/>
that the arrangement of dikes in the<lb/>
Primary Country of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag103"
                ref="#place_021"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag103" type="place">
          Cornwall
        </name>
            </rs>, &amp; in the<lb/>
Secondary Country of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag104"
                ref="#place_160"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag104" type="place">
          Somersetshire
        </name>
            </rs>, are very<lb/>
different. - In the one, the vein cut<lb/>
through, almost always appears shifted,<lb/>
&amp; in the other, it maintains its<lb/>
perpendicular direction. - And the<lb/>
mere knowledge of this fact, which is<lb/>
almost general for the different districts,<lb/>
would have insured the success of the<lb/>
operation. -<lb/>
--- A number of instances of the<lb/>
same kind might be adduced. - /_ And<lb/>
the Science is equally applicable in<lb/>
a number of other Arts &amp; Professions. -<lb/>
- It ought to be particularly studied<lb/>
by the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Engineer</hi>, who is employed<lb/>
in the construction of Canals, or Docks,<lb/>
or Fortifications, as certain strata<lb/>
exceedingly hard, often alternate<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="60"
                xml:id="pb-60"
                facs="#i60"/>
            <lb/>
with others that are very soft &amp; easily<lb/>
cut through, &amp; by a knowledge of their<lb/>
different positions &amp; relations, much<lb/>
unnecessary labour &amp; expence may<lb/>
be often avoided. -<lb/>
- - The Drainer, in order to make<lb/>
his <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">operations</hi> successful, ought to<lb/>
be minutely acquainted with the<lb/>
arrangement of the Rocks, in the<lb/>
district from which the springs arise,<lb/>
which it is his business to divert,<lb/>
&amp; he ought to pay particular attention<lb/>
to the nature &amp; position of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">dikes</hi>,<lb/>
for they often intersect soft strata,<lb/>
&amp; stop the course of the water,<lb/>
&amp; render all his operations useless,<lb/>
till they are discovered &amp; penetrated. -<lb/>
- The Farmer &amp; the Improver of Land<lb/>
even, may often derive from Geology<lb/>
very useful instruction with regard<lb/>
to the position of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag105"
                ref="#chemical_090"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag105">
          Limestone
          
        </term>
            </rs>, <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag106"
                ref="#chemical_112"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag106">
          Marle
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; Clays,<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="61"
                xml:id="pb-61"
                facs="#i61"/>
            <lb/>
their application, &amp; the nearest places<lb/>
whence they may be procured. - -<lb/>
And lastly, - Even the Architect may<lb/>
often benefit by this Science. - Of the<lb/>
strata which afford stones employed in<lb/>
Building - some parts are much more<lb/>
liable to decay than others, &amp; the<lb/>
external Character, affords the<lb/>
indication. - - Many rocks exceedingly<lb/>
beautiful &amp; tempting to the Eye, &amp;<lb/>
easily cut through, are often very<lb/>
liable to decomposition, to be easily<lb/>
destroyed by common natural agents;<lb/>
And their relations to permanency can<lb/>
only be known by Scientific Observation<lb/>
- I can mention two remarkable cases<lb/>
in which decomposing Stones have been<lb/>
unfortunately employed in the construction<lb/>
of considerable Edifices, which in<lb/>
consequence are most rapidly falling<lb/>
into decay. - The one is Chester<lb/>
Cathedral, which is constructed of<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="62"
                xml:id="pb-62"
                facs="#i62"/>
            <lb/>
ferruginous <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag107"
                ref="#chemical_088"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag107">
          Sandstone
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; by the<lb/>
action of water &amp; air, all the<lb/>
exterior ornaments, &amp; nearly a half<lb/>
of the surface of this venerable<lb/>
Structure are destroyed. -<lb/>
- The other, is the Library of Trinity<lb/>
College, Dublin, which must have<lb/>
been a most beautiful building<lb/>
but which from decomposition is rapidly<lb/>
losing all its elegance of Architecture,<lb/>
&amp; the circumstance is the more singular,<lb/>
as the principal rocks in the<lb/>
neighbourhood are beautiful &amp;<lb/>
permanent granites - &amp; by some<lb/>
unfortunate circumstance, the<lb/>
materials selected for this edifice<lb/>
must have been brought from<lb/>
some distance &amp; probably at a<lb/>
great expence. ---<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="63"
                xml:id="pb-63"
                facs="#i63"/>
            <lb/>
appellation<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="64"
                xml:id="pb-64"
                facs="#i64"/>
            <lb/>
Indeed<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">&amp;</del> there is no city in Europe more happily<lb/>
situated in this respect than Dublin.<lb/>
Its position is such that were a geological<lb/>
academy to be established it could<lb/>
not be fixed in a more advantageous<lb/>
spot - The mountains around us<lb/>
contain all the varieties of the<lb/>
Primary rocks; the strata beneath our<lb/>
feet are secondary: - &amp; the sides of<lb/>
vallies in the neighbourhood afford<lb/>
abundance of mineral veins -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="65"
                xml:id="pb-65"
                facs="#i65"/>
            <lb/>
17<lb/>
- It will be unnecessary to pursue<lb/>
these statements to any greater extent. -<lb/>
Sufficient has I trust been said, to<lb/>
prove that the Science may be of National,<lb/>
as well as of individual advantage -<lb/>
&amp; at least, to establish its Utility. -<lb/>
- It is far from my wish to endeavour<lb/>
to exalt Geology to a higher rank<lb/>
than it ought to occupy, or to attempt<lb/>
to raise it unfairly above the other<lb/>
branches of physical Knowledge. -<lb/>
- But I should be unjust to my Subject,<lb/>
were I not to state, some of the<lb/>
peculiar advantages which it possesses<lb/>
- as <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">a Science of Contemplation - &amp;</hi> as a<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">series of important truths,</hi> unfolding<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">some of the most beautiful &amp; harmonious</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">parts of the Economy of Nature. -</hi>
            <lb/>
- Of all material objects that<lb/>
can employ our attention, those that<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="66"
                xml:id="pb-66"
                facs="#i66"/>
            <lb/>
are nearest to us, ought to excite the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">warmest</hi> &amp; the most <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">immediate interest</hi>;<lb/>
And after Man, &amp; animated Nature,<lb/>
no subject of physical enquiry bears<lb/>
a more distinct relation to us, than<lb/>
the place of our abode, <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">the Earth</hi>,<lb/>
to which we are necessarily attached,<lb/>
&amp; the mechanism of which, is intimately<lb/>
connected with all our <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">powers</hi>,<lb/>
our enjoyments, &amp; even our existence. -<lb/>
- |_The mere <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">mere</add> general Study of the<lb/>
Science, of the Constitution of the Globe,<lb/>
affords some very beautiful &amp; sublime<lb/>
views which could never be gained<lb/>
from the common observation of external<lb/>
nature. - It explains the <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">uses &amp;</del>
            <lb/>
importance of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">variety</hi> &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">irregularities</hi>
            <lb/>
which it exhibits &amp; <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">demonstrates</hi>
            <lb/>
that no parts are useless. - &amp; that<lb/>
the causes which apparently produce<lb/>
destruction &amp; disorder are in fact,<lb/>
in the general series connected with<lb/>
the renovation &amp; support of the system.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="67"
                xml:id="pb-67"
                facs="#i67"/>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
